Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read the Prime Minister’s address for the latest information.

Anguilla has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Anguilla, see Return to the UK
Local measures
Anguilla’s ports, sea and air are closed for all passenger movements until at least 12:01am (local time) on Tuesday Sunday 31 May. This date is kept under constant review and may be extended.
The temporary restrictions on the movement of people and public gatherings were lifted on Wednesday 29 April. Further information on these measures can be found on the Government of Anguilla COVID-19 website and the Government of Anguilla website.
With effect from 17 March all persons who have travelled outside of the Caribbean Region within the previous 14 days will be quarantined for 14 days on arrival. A judgement will be made on arrival by health professionals if this can be self-quarantined or quarantined in a Government run health facility.
The regular ferry service from Marigot Port (French St. Martin) to Blowing Point Ferry Port has been suspended with effect from 19:00 (local time) on 17 March until further notice.
Princess Juliana International Airport on the neighbouring island of Dutch St. Maarten has restricted the entry of incoming visitors from the US, Canada and Europe with effect from Tuesday 17 March.
The Health Authority of Anguilla are asking the public to call the COVID-19 inquiries hotline on + 1 264 476 7627 if they suspect they might have contracted the coronavirus, been exposed to the coronavirus, or have any questions other matters relating to their health and coronavirus. The public are asked to call the hotline and not visit a healthcare facility unless instructed to.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
